Database Optimization
Optimization of databases is very important in any system. The purpose of the optimization process is to get the best performance from the system. Databases are optimized by following certain rules. Some of these rules include: indexing tables properly, reducing the number of tables, normalizing the data, etc. The aim of this essay is to discuss these rules in detail and provide an overview of their importance. Database Optimization
The first step in optimizing a database is to index tables properly. Indexing tables allows you to retrieve data faster because it reduces the amount of time that is needed to search through records. It also reduces disk usage which improves performance. There are two types of indexes available for use in Oracle: bitmap indexes and B-tree indexes. Bitmap indexes are used when there are many columns being searched at once such as when doing a full table scan or when searching on multiple columns with equal values (e.g., all rows where the last name starts with “A”). B-tree indexes are used when there are few columns being searched at once (e.g., searching on only one column). In addition, they can be used for large numbers of records where speed matters more than memory usage (i.e., if you have millions of records).
Reducing the number of tables in a system helps reduce disk space usage and improves performance because it eliminates unnecessary work that needs to be done during queries and updates. Normalizing the data means that each field contains only one value and does not contain redundant information about another field in another table (e.g., customer ID). This makes searching easier since you only need to search one table instead of two or three different ones depending on what you’re looking for (customer address vs. product description).
The final step in optimizing a database is to remove unnecessary columns from tables so that only those columns needed for querying purposes remain. This will improve performance because less work needs to be done when performing queries on these tables since less information needs to be retrieved from them before returning results back to users who requested them via web applications or other client applications such as Excel spreadsheets or word processing documents containing macros designed specifically for working with databases like Access databases created using Visual Basic programming language (VBA).
