Database Optimization is a process of improving the performance of a database system. It involves making changes to the structure of the database and its storage methods, as well as tuning the settings of the database engine itself. The goal is to make the database run faster and more efficiently.
The most common reason for optimizing a database is that it has become too slow for its intended purpose. This can happen when there are too many queries being executed against it, or when there is not enough memory available for storing data in memory (RAM). Another common reason is that there are too many transactions being processed by the database, which causes delays in processing transactions and reduces overall throughput.
The first step in optimizing a database is to identify what types of queries are causing problems. You should also look at how much memory your server has available for storing data in RAM, as well as how much disk space it uses for storing data on hard drives or SSDs (Solid State Drives). If you find that your server doesn’t have enough RAM or disk space, then you may need to upgrade your hardware before proceeding with optimization steps such as adding indexes or changing table structures so that they use less space than before but still allow fast access times when needed (for example: adding an index on an ID column instead of having multiple columns with unique values).

