In order to optimize a database, you must first identify what type of database you are working with. There are several types of databases: relational, object-oriented and hierarchical. Once you have identified the type of database you are working with, you can then begin to optimize it by using various techniques.
The first step in optimizing a database is to determine whether or not it is relational or non-relational. Relational databases store data in tables that consist of rows and columns. Non-relational databases do not use tables but rather store data in files. If your database is relational then you will need to perform the following steps:
– Create indexes on all columns that will be used frequently in queries;
– Create foreign keys between related tables;
– Create primary keys for each table;
– Make sure all columns have unique values;
– Remove duplicate entries from each table;
– Reduce the number of columns in each table by combining similar columns into one column;
– Add constraints such as not null constraints on some columns so that they cannot contain null values; and
– Use views whenever possible instead of tables when displaying information from multiple tables at once (for example, when displaying sales figures over time).
If your database is non-relational then you will need to perform the following steps:
– Create indexes on all fields that will be used frequently in queries;
– Create foreign keys between related records;
– Create primary keys for each record;
– Make sure all fields have unique values;
– Remove duplicate entries from each record;
– Reduce the number of fields in each record by combining similar fields into one field; and
– Add constraints such as not null constraints on some fields so that they cannot contain null values; and
– Use views whenever possible instead of records when displaying information from multiple records at once (for example, when displaying sales figures over time).
Finally, if your database is hierarchical then you will need to perform the following steps:
– Create indexes on all nodes that will be used frequently in queries;
– Create foreign keys between related nodes;
– Create primary keys for each node;
– Make sure all nodes have unique values;
– Remove duplicate entries from each node;
– Reduce the number of nodes in each node by combining similar nodes into one node; and
– Add constraints such as not null constraints on some nodes so that they cannot contain null values; and
– Use views whenever possible instead of nodes when displaying information from multiple nodes at once (for example, when displaying sales figures over time).

